WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.160
[Amit Varma]: A few years ago, a photograph went viral on Facebook. It was a picture of two girls hanging

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:15.720
[Amit Varma]: from a tree. It had been taken in the Badao district of Uttar Pradesh, and the girls were

00:00:15.720 --> 00:00:20.960
[Amit Varma]: 16 and 14 years old. Their slippers lay at the trunk of the tree. Later, we would find

00:00:20.960 --> 00:00:25.480
[Amit Varma]: that the women gathered there had come to protect the bodies of the girls with their

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:29.960
[Amit Varma]: bodies. And one of the patriarchs had decided that the girls would not be brought down from

00:00:29.960 --> 00:00:35.840
[Amit Varma]: the tree until justice was done. They turned away the police, they turned away local politicians.

00:00:35.840 --> 00:00:41.320
[Amit Varma]: Eventually, the world woke up and paid attention. Violence against women in India is commonplace.

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:45.920
[Amit Varma]: Rapes are commonplace. The statistics are overwhelming. And yet, this case captured

00:00:45.920 --> 00:00:50.520
[Amit Varma]: the imagination of the nation. Two girls go out in the late evening to defecate in an

00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:55.520
[Amit Varma]: open field. A few hours later, they are hanging from a tree. The family alleges that they

00:00:55.520 --> 00:01:00.240
[Amit Varma]: were gang raped. Later, others hinted on a killing. There is an angle of caste, there

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:04.880
[Amit Varma]: is an angle of local politics, there is misogyny everywhere. The early narratives around this

00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:09.000
[Amit Varma]: case turn out to be not quite true. And in fact, we may never know what happened that

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.600
[Amit Varma]: day. But this much is clear. A tragedy took place that night, two girls died, and we live

00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:26.480
[Unknown]: in a broken society. Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics,

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:31.480
[Unknown]: politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:36.040
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Sonia Falero, a journalist and writer

00:01:36.040 --> 00:01:41.320
[Amit Varma]: of narrative nonfiction, whose new book, The Good Girls, deals with the tragic incident

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:47.560
[Amit Varma]: I just mentioned in Katra, Sadatganj in the district of Badaun in Uttar Pradesh in 2014.

00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:52.080
[Amit Varma]: Sonia is an old friend, and we hung out for many years in the aughties till she shifted

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:56.440
[Amit Varma]: from Mumbai to London about a decade ago. She spent a fair bit of time reporting on

00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:01.660
[Amit Varma]: the farmer's suicides in Vidarbha. And once she found her voice, the focus of her journalism

00:02:01.660 --> 00:02:06.720
[Amit Varma]: was always on marginalized people. While she was in Mumbai, she wrote a superb book called

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:11.560
[Amit Varma]: The Beautiful Thing, chronicling the life of a bar dancer in Mumbai. I was privileged

00:02:11.560 --> 00:02:16.280
[Amit Varma]: enough to be privy to many drafts of that fine book, and was blown away by her craft

00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:20.860
[Amit Varma]: and work ethic. After she shifted away, she continued making regular trips to India, reporting

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:26.000
[Amit Varma]: from here. And a few years ago, she released a Kindle single called 13 Men, a stunning

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.520
[Amit Varma]: piece of reportage about the gang rape of a 20 year old in a village in West Bengal,

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:37.760
[Amit Varma]: also in 2014. 13 Men felt like a modern version of Rashomon. Her reporting was intensive,

00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:43.120
[Amit Varma]: she spoke to everyone, covered every angle. And yet at the end, you weren't quite sure

00:02:43.120 --> 00:02:48.040
[Amit Varma]: what had really happened. We sometimes deal with the complexity of the real world by building

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:54.000
[Amit Varma]: simple narratives or choosing simple narratives. But Sonia's work embraces that complexity

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:59.520
[Amit Varma]: and shines a light through its many layers. The Good Girls does exactly that. Sonia spent

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:04.400
[Amit Varma]: years researching and writing this book, and there is much in it that is not in the public

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:09.120
[Amit Varma]: domain, and that people don't know about this story. When the news of the two girls first

00:03:09.120 --> 00:03:14.360
[Amit Varma]: hit the media in 2014, it seemed like a clear case of gang rape and murder. And yet we now

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:19.600
[Amit Varma]: know that the early testimonies by the family were made up and motivated. Later, it seemed

00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:23.960
[Amit Varma]: that it might be an honor killing, but there's no evidence for that either. Although medieval

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:29.760
[Amit Varma]: notions of honor do play an important part. Sonia examines every angle, pulls every strand

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:35.480
[Amit Varma]: as far as it will go. And by the end, I was left with the sense that everyone is a victim

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:40.800
[Amit Varma]: in the story. And at the same time, everyone is complicit. You'll have to read the book

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:45.720
[Amit Varma]: to see what I mean. And despite the grim subject matter, it's a heck of a read with all the

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:50.640
[Amit Varma]: characters coming alive for us. I finished the book in one sitting, and so will you.

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:54.440
[Amit Varma]: I spent a big chunk of the conversation you're about to hear talking about Sonia's writing

00:03:54.440 --> 00:04:00.600
[Amit Varma]: process and her approach to journalism, especially in India. Her process is both daunting and

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:06.520
[Amit Varma]: inspiring. And while I know many, many journalists, I don't know anyone quite like Sonia Falero.

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:11.040
[Amit Varma]: You'll see what I mean when you hear her talk about her work and when you read her books.

00:04:11.040 --> 00:04:18.240
[Amit Varma]: But before we begin, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:04:18.240 --> 00:04:21.960
[Amit Varma]: Many years ago, I could not have done this podcast and you would not be listening to

00:04:21.960 --> 00:04:27.080
[Amit Varma]: me in the way that you are now. Digital technology has changed our lives. And it's kind of sad

